{"kind":"project","sections":[{"estimatedTimeInMinutes":15,"kind":"hero","content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Now we have a working API and a way to test it, lets look into storing our todos in a Postgres database with PostgresNIO."}],"type":"paragraph"}],"image":"hummingbird.png","chapter":"Store Todos in a database","backgroundImage":"hummingbird.png","title":"Use PostgresNIO to store your Todos in a Postgres database"},{"tasks":[{"stepsSection":[{"code":"todos-postgres-01.sh","caption":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Once you have installed Postgres follow the instructions on screen to start your Postgres database service.","type":"text"}]}],"type":"step","media":null,"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"You’ll need to install postgres on your system if you don’t already have it. Detailed instructions on installing Postgres can be found ","type":"text"},{"isActive":true,"identifier":"https:\/\/www.postgresql.org\/download\/","type":"reference"},{"text":".","type":"text"}]}],"runtimePreview":null},{"code":"todos-postgres-02.sh","caption":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Note the SQL commands all end in a semi-colon. The "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"\\c"},{"type":"text","text":" command connects to a database and the "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"\\q"},{"type":"text","text":" command quits "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"pqsl"},{"type":"text","text":". You can find out more about "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"psql"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"reference","identifier":"https:\/\/www.postgresql.org\/docs\/current\/app-psql.html","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":"."}],"type":"paragraph"}],"type":"step","media":null,"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The Postgres install comes with "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"psql"},{"type":"text","text":" the commandline interface to Postgres. We are going to use this to create a new database and a new role."}],"type":"paragraph"}],"runtimePreview":null},{"code":"todos-postgres-03.swift","caption":[],"type":"step","media":null,"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"We return to our project…","type":"text"}]}],"runtimePreview":null},{"code":"todos-postgres-04.swift","caption":[],"type":"step","media":null,"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"And add PostgresNIO as a dependency","type":"text"}]}],"runtimePreview":null},{"code":"todos-postgres-05.swift","caption":[],"type":"step","media":null,"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"In Sources\/App\/Application+build.swift…","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}],"runtimePreview":null},{"code":"todos-postgres-06.swift","caption":[],"type":"step","media":null,"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"we add a new requirement "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"inMemoryTesting"},{"type":"text","text":" to "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"AppArguments"},{"type":"text","text":". This will decide whether we store Todos in memory or a Postgres database."}],"type":"paragraph"}],"runtimePreview":null},{"code":"todos-postgres-07.swift","caption":[],"type":"step","media":null,"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"We then need to add implementations of this requirement in Sources\/App\/App.swift","type":"text"}]}],"runtimePreview":null},{"code":"todos-postgres-08.swift","caption":[],"type":"step","media":null,"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"and Tests\/AppTests\/AppTests.swift","type":"text"}]}],"runtimePreview":null},{"code":"todos-postgres-09.swift","caption":[],"type":"step","media":null,"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"We are going to use "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"PostgresClient"},{"type":"text","text":" from PostgresNIO for our Postgres support. The "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"inMemoryTesting"},{"type":"text","text":" flag is used to decide on whether we should set one up. Note the Postgres configuration details are the same as the Postgres role we set up earlier in psql."}]}],"runtimePreview":null},{"code":"todos-postgres-10.swift","caption":[],"type":"step","media":null,"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"codeVoice","code":"PostgresClient"},{"type":"text","text":" sets up background processes that requires lifecycle management. You can add a service to "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Application"},{"type":"text","text":" to have its lifecycle managed as long as it conforms to "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Service"},{"type":"text","text":". This is done by adding it to an internally held "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"ServiceGroup"},{"type":"text","text":". More details on "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Service"},{"type":"text","text":" and "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"ServiceGroup"},{"type":"text","text":" can be found in the documentation for "},{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"identifier":"https:\/\/swiftpackageindex.com\/swift-server\/swift-service-lifecycle\/main\/documentation\/servicelifecycle"},{"type":"text","text":"."}],"type":"paragraph"}],"runtimePreview":null}],"anchor":"Setup-your-Postgres-database","contentSection":[{"mediaPosition":"trailing","kind":"contentAndMedia","media":"hummingbird.png","content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Setup a Postgres database to use with the Todos application."}],"type":"paragraph"}]}],"title":"Setup your Postgres database"},{"stepsSection":[{"code":"todos-postgres-11.swift","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"We start our Postgres support by creating a type conforming to "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"TodoRepository"},{"type":"text","text":" that uses "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"PostgresClient"},{"type":"text","text":" from PostgresNIO. The functions are filled out with dummy code just now so the project will compile."}]}],"type":"step","runtimePreview":null,"caption":[],"media":null},{"code":"todos-postgres-12.swift","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"If we are going to be saving our todos to a database we are going to need a table to store them in.","type":"text"}]}],"type":"step","runtimePreview":null,"caption":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"I won’t go into any great detail about the SQL calls. That is not the purpose of this tutorial. We will cover how you construct, send calls and parse their results with "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"PostgresClient"},{"type":"text","text":" as we proceed through the tutorial."}]}],"media":null},{"code":"todos-postgres-10.swift","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Return to ","type":"text"},{"code":"buildApplication(_:)","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" in Application+build.swift…","type":"text"}]}],"type":"step","runtimePreview":null,"caption":[],"media":null},{"code":"todos-postgres-14.swift","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Use the newly created "},{"code":"TodoPostgresRepository","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" and once the "},{"code":"PostgresClient","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" is running call "},{"code":"createTable","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":"."}]}],"type":"step","runtimePreview":null,"caption":[],"media":null},{"code":"todos-postgres-23.swift","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Update "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"buildRouter(_:)"},{"type":"text","text":" to take the repository as an argument and pass it to the controller."}]}],"type":"step","runtimePreview":null,"caption":[],"media":null},{"code":"todos-postgres-12.swift","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Back to TodoPostgresRepository.swift to start implementing our repository methods."}]}],"type":"step","runtimePreview":null,"caption":[],"media":null},{"code":"todos-postgres-15.swift","content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"To run a SQL query call "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"PostgresClient.query(_:logger:)"},{"type":"text","text":" with the query string and a Logger`."}],"type":"paragraph"}],"type":"step","runtimePreview":null,"caption":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Wait a sec! If you look closer that query looks like it’s got SQL injection. That’s a classic security issue. Except this isn’t the case here. The object being constructed is not a ","type":"text"},{"code":"String","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" but a ","type":"text"},{"code":"PostgresQuery","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" which uses ","type":"text"},{"code":"StringInterpolation","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" to create parameter bindings for all the interpolated variables.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}],"media":null},{"code":"todos-postgres-16.swift","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"get"},{"type":"text","text":" method demonstrates how you get data returned from a query. The query returns a sequence of rows. You extract the data from the row by decoding it as a tuple. In this case there should only be one row so we return immediately as soon as we have it."}]}],"type":"step","runtimePreview":null,"caption":[],"media":null},{"code":"todos-postgres-17.swift","content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"codeVoice","code":"list"},{"type":"text","text":" is very similar to "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"get"},{"type":"text","text":". Except there is no "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"WHERE"},{"type":"text","text":" clause in the SQL and we return all of the rows returned from the query instead of just the first."}],"type":"paragraph"}],"type":"step","runtimePreview":null,"caption":[],"media":null},{"code":"todos-postgres-18.swift","content":[{"inlineContent":[{"code":"patch","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" has a complication where we only want to include the non optional values in the "},{"code":"UPDATE","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" query otherwise we’ll be setting database columns to null. You could do this dynamically and build a "},{"code":"PostgresQuery.StringInterpolation","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" bit by bit but it is safer just to provide the full query strings for each situation."}],"type":"paragraph"}],"type":"step","runtimePreview":null,"caption":[],"media":null},{"code":"todos-postgres-20.swift","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"And finally the "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"delete"},{"type":"text","text":" and "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"deleteAll"},{"type":"text","text":" functions. This completes the implementation of the Postgres todos repository."}]}],"type":"step","runtimePreview":null,"caption":[],"media":null},{"code":"todos-postgres-21.swift","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"If you go to Tests\/AppTests\/AppTests.swift…"}]}],"type":"step","runtimePreview":null,"caption":[],"media":null},{"code":"todos-postgres-22.swift","content":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"You can switch the ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"inMemoryTesting"},{"text":" boolean to false to test your Postgres solution.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}],"type":"step","runtimePreview":null,"caption":[],"media":null},{"code":null,"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"That’s us done, we have a working and tested Todos application.","type":"text"}]}],"type":"step","runtimePreview":null,"caption":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"The code for this tutorial can be found in the ","type":"text"},{"isActive":true,"type":"reference","identifier":"https:\/\/github.com\/hummingbird-project\/hummingbird-examples\/tree\/main\/todos-postgres-tutorial"},{"text":".","type":"text"}]}],"media":null}],"anchor":"Setup-a-Postgres-repository","contentSection":[{"mediaPosition":"trailing","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Implement a version of ","type":"text"},{"code":"TodoRepository","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" that uses ","type":"text"},{"code":"PostgresClient"